Inheritance allows a child class to acquire the properties and methods of a parent class, enabling code reuse and forming the basis for polymorphism.

**Single: ****One child extends one parent — fully supported in TypeScript.**

**Multi-level: ****Chain of inheritance A → B → C — supported in TypeScript.**

**Hierarchical: ****Multiple child classes extend one parent — supported in TypeScript.**

**Multiple: ****One child extends multiple parents — not supported directly in TypeScript; use interfaces instead.**

**Hybrid: ****Combination of the above — achievable via interfaces in TypeScript.**

// Runtime Polymorphism (Override)

class Animal {

  speak(): string { return 'Some sound'; }

  }

class Dog extends Animal {

  speak(): string { return 'Woof!'; }

  }

class Cat extends Animal {

  speak(): string { return 'Meow!'; }

  }

// Compile-time Polymorphism (Overload)

class Calculator {

  add(a: number, b: number): number;

  add(a: string, b: string): string;

  add(a: any, b: any): any { return a + b; }

  }

// Runtime dispatch

const animals: Animal[] = [new Dog(), new Cat(), new Animal()];

animals.forEach(a => console.log(a.speak()));

// 'Woof!', 'Meow!', 'Some sound'

Polymorphism ('many forms') lets the same interface produce different behaviour depending on the concrete type at runtime, or at compile time through overloading.

**Compile-time (Static): ****Resolved at compile time via method overloading or operator overloading (e.g. add(int) vs add(string)).**

**Runtime (Dynamic): ****Resolved at runtime via method overriding — the correct subclass implementation is dispatched (e.g. animal.speak() calls Dog.speak() or Cat.speak()).**

**Key benefit: ****Write code against a base type; at runtime the correct subclass behaviour is automatically invoked — open/closed by nature.**

