Dependency Injection (DI) is a pattern in which a class receives its dependencies from an external source rather than creating them internally. It is the practical application of the Dependency Inversion Principle.

**Without DI: ****Tight coupling — the class hardcodes new MySQLDatabase() and new SMTPEmailer(), making it impossible to swap implementations or inject mocks.**

**With DI: ****Dependencies are injected via the constructor; the class depends on interfaces (Database, Emailer), not concrete classes.**

**Benefits: ****Loose coupling, easier unit testing (inject MockDatabase), and simpler swapping of implementations in production vs. test environments.**

**Common in: ****NestJS, Angular, and most enterprise frameworks that provide a DI container.**

// Aggregation: Department can exist without Employees

