The Single Responsibility Principle states that each class should have exactly one reason to change — it should be responsible for only one part of the system's functionality.

**Violation: ****A single UserService that creates users, sends emails, generates PDF reports, and logs activity — too many responsibilities.**

**Compliant: ****Separate into UserService, EmailService, ReportService, and UserValidator — each handles one concern.**

**Test: ****Ask: 'If this business rule changes, does this class need to change?' Multiple yes answers signal an SRP violation.**

// VI PHAM OCP: thêm discount mới phải sửa hàm

function getDiscount(type: string, price: number): number {

  if (type === 'vip')    return price * 0.2;

  if (type === 'member') return price * 0.1;

  // Muốn thêm 'student' -> phải sửa hàm này!

  return 0;

  }

// TUAN THU OCP: mở rộng bằng cách thêm class mới

interface DiscountStrategy {

  calculate(price: number): number;

  }

class VipDiscount    implements DiscountStrategy { calculate(p) { return p * 0.2; } }

class MemberDiscount implements DiscountStrategy { calculate(p) { return p * 0.1; } }

class StudentDiscount implements DiscountStrategy { calculate(p) { return p * 0.15; } }

class PriceCalculator {

  constructor(private strategy: DiscountStrategy) {}

  getFinalPrice(price: number): number {

    return price - this.strategy.calculate(price);

  }

  }

// Thêm discount mới: chỉ cần tạo class mới, không sửa code cũ

The Open/Closed Principle states that a class should be open for extension but closed for modification — add new behaviour by adding new code, not by editing existing code.

**Violation: ****A getDiscount() function with if/else branches for each discount type — adding a new type requires modifying the function.**

**Compliant: ****Define a DiscountStrategy interface; each discount type is a new class (VipDiscount, StudentDiscount) — no existing code changes.**

**How to achieve: ****Use interfaces, abstract classes, the Strategy pattern, or composition to introduce new behaviour without touching existing logic.**

// VI PHAM LSP: Square extends Rectangle

class Rectangle {

  constructor(protected width: number, protected height: number) {}

  setWidth(w: number)  { this.width = w; }

  setHeight(h: number) { this.height = h; }

  area() { return this.width * this.height; }

  }

class Square extends Rectangle {

  setWidth(w: number)  { this.width = this.height = w; }  // làm sai Rectangle!

  setHeight(h: number) { this.width = this.height = h; }

  }

function resize(rect: Rectangle) {

  rect.setWidth(5); rect.setHeight(10);

  // Expect area = 50, nhưng Square trả về 100!

  }

// TUAN THU LSP: không kế thừa bật buộc

abstract class Shape { abstract area(): number; }

class Rectangle2 extends Shape {

  constructor(public width: number, public height: number) { super(); }

  area() { return this.width * this.height; }

  }

class Square2 extends Shape {

  constructor(public side: number) { super(); }

  area() { return this.side ** 2; }

  }

The Liskov Substitution Principle states that objects of a subclass must be substitutable for objects of the superclass without altering the correctness of the program.

**Violation: ****Square extends Rectangle and overrides setWidth/setHeight to keep both dimensions equal — this breaks the Rectangle contract (setWidth then setHeight should give width × height).**

**Compliant: ****Square and Rectangle both extend a common abstract Shape; each has its own independent area() — no contract is broken.**

**Rule of thumb: ****If substituting a subtype causes unexpected behaviour, the inheritance hierarchy violates LSP — prefer composition.**

// VI PHAM ISP: một interface quá lớn

interface Machine {

  print():  void;

  scan():   void;

  fax():    void;

  staple(): void;

  }

// SimplePrinter bị buộc implement scan, fax, staple!

class SimplePrinter implements Machine {

  print()  { console.log('Printing...'); }

  scan()   { throw new Error('Not supported'); } // lãng phí!

  fax()    { throw new Error('Not supported'); }

  staple() { throw new Error('Not supported'); }

  }

// TUAN THU ISP: tách interface nhỏ

interface Printable  { print(): void; }

interface Scannable  { scan():  void; }

interface Faxable    { fax():   void; }

class SimplePrinter2 implements Printable {

  print() { console.log('Printing...'); }

  }

class AllInOne implements Printable, Scannable, Faxable {

  print() { /* ... */ }

  scan()  { /* ... */ }

  fax()   { /* ... */ }

  }

The Interface Segregation Principle states that no client should be forced to depend on methods it does not use. Prefer many small, focused interfaces over one large general-purpose interface.

**Violation: ****A Machine interface with print(), scan(), fax(), and staple() forces SimplePrinter to implement methods it doesn't support, throwing 'Not supported' errors.**

**Compliant: ****Split into Printable, Scannable, and Faxable; SimplePrinter implements only Printable; AllInOne implements all three.**

**Benefit: ****Classes only depend on the interface members they actually use — leaner contracts and less fragile code.**

